{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"33ba4dfb-3508-4c33-8456-e4885965e720","content":"## What's happening\n\n.NET has been **progressively raising the minimum x86-64 microarchitecture level**. Starting with .NET 9, Linux x86-64 required **x86-64-v2** (SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT). .NET 11 likely raised this to **x86-64-v3**, which requires **AVX2, BMI1/2, FMA**, etc.\n\nYour 2012-era hardware predates **Haswell** (2013) — the first x86 microarchitecture with AVX2. That's why it fails at startup.\n\n## Your other targets are fine\n\n| Target | Status | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| Linux x86-64 (post-2013) | ✅ | Haswell+ supports x86-64-v3 |\n| Linux x86-64 (2012 node) | ❌ | Pre-Haswell, no AVX2 |\n| Windows Arm64 (SQ1) | ✅ | ARM baseline unaffected |\n| Raspberry Pi 4 (Cortex-A72) | ✅ | ARM baseline unaffected |\n\n## How to confirm & fix\n\n1. **Check the failing node's CPU:** `lscpu | grep -i \"model name\\|Flags\"` — look for the absence of `avx2`.\n2. **Options:**\n   - **Replace the hardware** (cheapest long-term — Haswell-era servers are 10+ years old).\n   - **Stay on .NET 10** for workloads targeting that node until hardware is retired.\n   - Check if Microsoft offers a **v2-baseline build** of the .NET 11 runtime (they did this during the v1→v2 transition).\n\nThe runtime performs this CPU check at startup before any managed code runs, so there's no workaround via code changes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ef41238a-84b6-48e0-ad6a-05c21888c936","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly without needing tools.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. But actually, let me think more carefully about the timeline.\n\nActually, .NET 9 raised the baseline to x86-64-v2 for Linux. The user says they're upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, and some hardware dates back to 2012. \n\nWait - if they were running .NET 10 fine, then the baseline change must have happened between .NET 10 and .NET 11, not in .NET 9. Let me reconsider what I know about the actual timeline for when these baseline changes occurred.\n\nThe issue is that their 2012 hardware supports SSE4.2 but not AVX2, so if .NET 11 raised the baseline to x86-64-v3 (which requires AVX2), that would explain why they hit this error only after upgrading. AVX2 didn't arrive until Haswell in 2013, so raising the baseline to v3 would indeed break compatibility with 2012 hardware. The most likely scenario is that .NET 9 moved to v2 baseline, .NET 10 maintained that requirement (which the user's older hardware could handle), and .NET 11 may have bumped it further to v3, which would explain the failure on pre-Haswell systems. as fact versus speculation. The error message itself is a .NET runtime check that triggers when the CPU lacks required baseline instruction sets. For .NET 9 and later, the x86-64 baseline is v2, which older hardware from around 2012 typically supports. If .NET 11 raised the baseline to v3 (requiring AVX2 from Haswell onward in 2013), that would explain why the user's older CPU is failing. I should explain the baseline mechanism and note that .NET has been progressively raising these requirements, then suggest they check their specific CPU against the baseline requirements.","outputTokens":1858,"requestId":"702A:E3CA7:5C8F51D:6479B49:69FBEEB9"},"id":"5d875da5-bfa5-405d-81b8-a8030f41b736","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:46:10.155Z","parentId":"1313da5a-3c47-4791-982f-b80b9fcde48b"}
